WEBVTT

00:02.136 --> 00:04.238
<i>♪ MTV ♪</i>

00:06.774 --> 00:09.277
[Nathan] <i>How long is
your family staying, Tommy?</i>

00:09.410 --> 00:11.379
[Tommy]
<i>Only one of 'em is my family,</i>

00:11.512 --> 00:12.613
and I'm working on it.

00:12.746 --> 00:13.647
Work faster.

00:13.781 --> 00:14.882
[grunts]

00:15.015 --> 00:16.617
[Jimenez]
We don't want your oil here.

00:16.717 --> 00:18.619
[Tommy] You sell a product that
your customers are dependent on.

00:18.719 --> 00:19.987
Yes.

00:20.121 --> 00:22.556
[Tommy] It's the same.
Ours is just bigger.

00:22.723 --> 00:24.625
[Rebecca]
<i>Here's what you're going to do.</i>

00:24.725 --> 00:25.926
You are going to take

00:26.026 --> 00:27.995
your eight-figure settlement
like men.

00:28.129 --> 00:29.363
[Tommy laughing]

00:29.530 --> 00:30.664
I'm sorry.

00:30.798 --> 00:32.900
We're not negotiating.
This is a surrender.

00:33.067 --> 00:36.570
Successful relationships
require sacrifice.

00:36.704 --> 00:38.172
It's a huge mistake.

00:38.306 --> 00:39.807
Say yes.

00:40.641 --> 00:43.311
- Oh, stop, stop! [shouts]
- Get on the blocks, worm.

00:43.444 --> 00:44.645
- What?
- Kill the rig!

00:44.745 --> 00:45.813
How'd it go?

00:45.946 --> 00:47.115
She's running.

00:47.215 --> 00:48.182
Well, I don't like gambling,

00:48.316 --> 00:49.783
but it paid off this time.

00:49.883 --> 00:51.752
[Ariana]
<i>Cooper, I need to see you.</i>

00:51.919 --> 00:53.354
Can you do that for me?

00:53.487 --> 00:55.923
Yeah. Yeah, I can do that.

00:56.056 --> 00:58.692
Are we moving here for good?
[squeals]

00:58.826 --> 00:59.727
[Angela laughs]

00:59.893 --> 01:02.230
I must be out
of my fucking mind.

01:04.064 --> 01:05.899
<i>♪ slow, gentle music ♪</i>

01:06.234 --> 01:08.169
<i>***</i>

01:34.295 --> 01:35.463
[Dale]
Yeah, it's about the same

01:35.596 --> 01:37.298
as the one we just worked over.

01:38.466 --> 01:39.467
[grunts]

01:40.534 --> 01:42.236
We should work
this whole field over.

01:42.370 --> 01:46.207
I mean, these are all 35 years
or more in production.

01:46.307 --> 01:48.008
How many total, Boss?

01:48.876 --> 01:50.878
Uh, 17, I think.

01:50.978 --> 01:53.347
- All right.
- [sinister ringtone playing]

01:54.215 --> 01:56.083
Oh, shit.

01:56.217 --> 01:57.818
Morning, honey.

01:57.985 --> 01:59.553
Let's make a new rule.

01:59.687 --> 02:03.591
Any time you spend the night
banging me on all fours,

02:03.724 --> 02:06.227
you take my call the next
morning, you fucking asshole.

02:06.327 --> 02:07.961
Honey, I'm working, okay?

02:08.128 --> 02:09.763
- See?
<i>- Aww, hi, boys.</i>

02:09.897 --> 02:11.332
- Hey, Ange.
<i>- It's so early.</i>

02:11.499 --> 02:13.967
Well, you know what they say
the early bird gets.

02:14.134 --> 02:16.304
Well, I know what
he could've gotten.

02:16.437 --> 02:17.671
- [Boss] Oh!
- [Dale] Oh!

02:17.805 --> 02:20.741
- [chuckles]
- Honey, they just saw that.

02:20.874 --> 02:22.476
[laughs]
Who cares?

02:22.643 --> 02:24.345
I'm just having fun.

02:24.478 --> 02:25.779
When will you be home?

02:25.913 --> 02:28.182
I don't know, probably late.
We're checking wells.

02:28.349 --> 02:30.984
<i>- In time for supper?</i>
- Maybe?

02:31.151 --> 02:33.086
Well, you better be.
Cooper's coming.

02:33.187 --> 02:35.456
- It's family dinner night.
- Since when?

02:35.589 --> 02:38.359
Since I thought of it
when I woke up this morning.

02:38.492 --> 02:40.328
Let's say 7.

02:41.862 --> 02:44.765
<i>I got to drive
a 300-mile loop, honey.</i>

02:47.335 --> 02:48.869
Do you think

02:49.036 --> 02:52.506
you can apply
a little fucking effort

02:52.673 --> 02:55.175
into repairing the damage
that's been done to our family?

02:55.343 --> 02:56.544
What damage
are you talking about?

02:56.710 --> 02:58.111
All I said is I'm working,

02:58.246 --> 03:00.248
and I'll get there when I can.

03:00.348 --> 03:02.450
Picking up right where
we fucking left off, huh?

03:02.550 --> 03:04.418
Exactly. Picking up
where we left off,

03:04.518 --> 03:06.820
which is what
I fucking told you.

03:06.954 --> 03:08.522
<i>Geez.</i>

03:08.656 --> 03:10.190
<i>Grumpy.</i>

03:10.324 --> 03:13.494
Okay. I'll see you at 7.

03:13.627 --> 03:14.862
I love you.

03:14.995 --> 03:16.397
All right,
yeah, I love you, too.

03:16.530 --> 03:17.765
<i>Oh, and I'm gonna do
a little more shopping.</i>

03:17.865 --> 03:19.967
<i>This place looks
like a fucking frat house.</i>

03:20.100 --> 03:21.969
But don't worry, I still have
Victor's credit card, okay?

03:22.069 --> 03:23.737
Love you. Bye.

03:23.871 --> 03:25.138
Love you, honey. Bye.

03:25.239 --> 03:26.274
[phone chimes]

03:27.941 --> 03:31.412
So, you and Angela.

03:31.545 --> 03:33.013
Giving it another go.

03:33.146 --> 03:35.983
Yeah, we're trying to.

03:36.083 --> 03:37.885
It's pretty hard to say no
to her when she's not--

03:38.018 --> 03:39.620
- Dressed? Yeah.
- Yeah.

03:39.720 --> 03:40.888
- [laughs]
- [Dale] Well, is she aware

03:41.021 --> 03:42.523
that Nate and I are gonna be

03:42.656 --> 03:45.058
at this dinner, you know,
'cause we fucking live there?

03:45.192 --> 03:47.027
She's not thinking
that deep inside it, Dale.

03:47.160 --> 03:49.062
- [laughs]
- [Boss] Can I come to dinner?

03:49.196 --> 03:50.464
I mean, I don't want to eat.

03:50.564 --> 03:52.266
I just want to sit
in the corner and watch her.

03:52.400 --> 03:54.001
[chuckles]
Why not?

03:54.101 --> 03:56.169
We can use all the witnesses
we can get.

03:56.304 --> 03:57.638
[chuckles]

03:57.738 --> 03:59.473
[sighs]

04:01.975 --> 04:04.177
[line ringing]

04:05.346 --> 04:07.415
[phone ringing]

04:07.548 --> 04:09.417
- Yeah?
- [Tommy over phone] <i>Hey, Monty.</i>

04:09.583 --> 04:11.785
<i>Listen, these Andrews wells
are underperforming.</i>

04:11.952 --> 04:14.855
<i>They're about the same age
as that other one</i>

04:14.988 --> 04:17.791
<i>the other day
and about the same production.</i>

04:17.958 --> 04:20.761
Do you want us to keep this
work-over crew going or what?

04:20.894 --> 04:23.531
[sighs]
How many wells?

04:23.664 --> 04:24.598
Seventeen.

04:24.732 --> 04:26.534
Well, I don't like
pressing my luck.

04:26.667 --> 04:28.402
Look, they all pull
from the same field,

04:28.536 --> 04:31.539
so there's no risk,
there's just expense.

04:31.672 --> 04:34.475
And Monty, the things are old,
and they need to be serviced.

04:34.642 --> 04:37.144
I mean, that last one
was proof of that, wasn't it?

04:37.277 --> 04:39.146
Work them over one at a time.

04:39.279 --> 04:40.514
I want to see
new production reports

04:40.614 --> 04:43.451
- before you start the next one.
<i>- Yes, sir.</i>

04:43.617 --> 04:45.252
All right.

04:45.386 --> 04:47.287
<i>♪ slow, somber music ♪</i>

04:47.421 --> 04:49.490
My God. I'll tell you what,

04:49.657 --> 04:51.224
trying to get money
from a billionaire

04:51.325 --> 04:52.560
is like pulling teeth.

04:52.660 --> 04:53.961
I mean, you would've
thought I just asked

04:54.127 --> 04:56.397
- the fucking guy for a kidney.
- [laughter]

04:56.530 --> 04:58.432
Well, that's how he became
a billionaire.

04:58.566 --> 04:59.833
No, he became a billionaire

04:59.967 --> 05:01.802
from betting everything
on black, and he hit.

05:01.935 --> 05:03.971
That's how you stay
a billionaire.

05:04.104 --> 05:07.140
Once you get the house's money,
you start pinching every penny.

05:07.307 --> 05:08.342
You know,
that's what I need to find.

05:08.509 --> 05:09.910
Some of that
fucking house money.

05:10.010 --> 05:11.244
No, what you need to do

05:11.345 --> 05:12.813
is quit getting
fucking divorced, dude.

05:12.980 --> 05:14.782
- [Dale laughs]
- No, what you both need to do

05:14.915 --> 05:16.750
is stop getting fucking married.

05:16.850 --> 05:20.654
If ever two people should be
single, you two motherfuckers.

05:20.821 --> 05:23.156
- You forget, I know your wife.
- Uh-huh.

05:23.323 --> 05:25.493
You run from her
like a scalded dog.

05:25.659 --> 05:27.895
- Oh. [laughs]
- So don't give me that shit.

05:27.995 --> 05:30.498
Okay, maybe so.

05:31.264 --> 05:32.666
But she don't call me

05:32.800 --> 05:34.368
at 8 in the morning,
buck-ass naked

05:34.535 --> 05:36.036
- for all my friends to see.
- [Dale laughs]

05:36.203 --> 05:38.005
And then chew my ass out

05:38.138 --> 05:39.607
before telling me
she's going shopping

05:39.707 --> 05:41.174
with another man's credit card.

05:41.341 --> 05:43.411
You say that
like it's a bad thing.

05:44.512 --> 05:46.547
- [engine starts]
- [laughs]

05:48.015 --> 05:50.551
[engine starts]

06:05.999 --> 06:07.735
<i>♪ gentle music ♪</i>

06:08.068 --> 06:09.970
<i>***</i>

06:28.722 --> 06:31.091
<i>***</i>

06:52.245 --> 06:54.314
<i>***</i>

07:22.743 --> 07:24.111
[shifter clicks]

07:24.244 --> 07:25.879
[engine turns off]

07:28.549 --> 07:30.017
<i>♪ slow, somber music ♪</i>

07:30.283 --> 07:32.520
<i>***</i>

07:53.941 --> 07:54.875
[doorbell rings]

08:06.319 --> 08:09.089
- Hey.
- Hey.

08:10.123 --> 08:11.525
Thanks for coming.

08:14.094 --> 08:17.364
- Come in.
- I'm, uh...

08:20.100 --> 08:21.368
It's fine. I'm used to it.

08:21.501 --> 08:23.737
You can take them off in here.

08:31.845 --> 08:33.246
[exhales]

08:41.221 --> 08:42.623
[Ariana sighs]

08:47.294 --> 08:48.662
When someone dies,

08:48.796 --> 08:52.232
it is tears and meals
and then a funeral.

08:52.365 --> 08:54.034
And then the business of death.

08:55.869 --> 08:58.906
Elvio did all the papers.

08:59.039 --> 09:01.441
None of it makes sense to me.

09:03.043 --> 09:04.745
Okay. Uh...

09:06.013 --> 09:07.214
[sighs]

09:10.050 --> 09:12.886
Okay, so this is, uh,
this is your mortgage statement.

09:13.053 --> 09:15.022
Looks like he's got it set up
on auto debit.

09:15.155 --> 09:17.457
$1,347 a month?

09:17.557 --> 09:19.559
And this one is...

09:19.693 --> 09:21.161
car insurance.

09:21.261 --> 09:23.530
$325 a month.

09:23.664 --> 09:25.065
You have any credit cards?

09:25.198 --> 09:28.068
- Uh, a debit card.
- Okay.

09:29.136 --> 09:30.671
Is this your only bank account?

09:30.804 --> 09:32.339
I don't know.

09:34.842 --> 09:36.777
Well, you've got $17,000
in this account.

09:36.910 --> 09:38.578
That's pretty good.

09:38.712 --> 09:42.249
That's gonna cover these bills
for about six months.

09:43.751 --> 09:45.786
I got to sell the house.

09:47.755 --> 09:50.658
Well, look, you're just
trading mortgage for rent.

09:52.626 --> 09:54.061
I would sell the truck.

09:54.194 --> 09:55.428
- It's paid for.
- [baby fussing]

09:55.562 --> 09:57.464
Plus, brings
your insurance down,

09:57.631 --> 09:59.266
lowers your expenses.

09:59.399 --> 10:01.068
[baby crying]

10:09.376 --> 10:11.111
[Ariana shushing]

10:13.280 --> 10:16.717
Um, Elvio was contributing
to a 401(k).

10:16.817 --> 10:18.485
I'm not sure exactly
how much is in there,

10:18.652 --> 10:21.321
but that's your money.

10:21.454 --> 10:23.290
I can ask how you collect it--

10:23.423 --> 10:24.725
Uh...
[clears throat]

10:24.858 --> 10:27.695
[chuckles]
I'll-I'll give you a minute.

10:33.801 --> 10:36.336
[baby fussing]

10:44.577 --> 10:46.947
Hey, you have a lawnmower?

10:47.080 --> 10:48.849
<i>♪ dramatic music ♪</i>

10:49.182 --> 10:51.719
<i>***</i>

11:12.806 --> 11:14.007
- Thank you.
- Right this way, please.

11:14.174 --> 11:15.308
All right.

11:15.442 --> 11:18.846
[Bob] <i>Our concern
isn't combustion engine</i>

11:18.979 --> 11:20.680
regulations
so much as it is the--

11:20.814 --> 11:22.682
- [man] It's not a concern, Bob?
- [Bob] It's not <i>the</i> concern.

11:22.816 --> 11:24.617
I mean,
60% of American electricity

11:24.752 --> 11:26.419
still comes from fossil fuels,

11:26.519 --> 11:28.355
39.8 from natural gas alone,

11:28.488 --> 11:30.123
and that number is climbing.

11:30.257 --> 11:32.392
Now, nuclear, that's maxed out,

11:32.525 --> 11:33.593
unless they build more reactors,

11:33.693 --> 11:35.528
and that's not gonna happen.

11:35.662 --> 11:37.865
Nuclear's not an option
for climate change advocates,

11:38.031 --> 11:39.032
even though it's our cleanest

11:39.166 --> 11:40.600
and most reliable
form of energy.

11:40.700 --> 11:42.602
Wind is twice
as expensive as natural gas,

11:42.702 --> 11:44.704
and solar,
four times as expensive.

11:44.872 --> 11:46.874
Plus, on its best day
of the year,

11:47.040 --> 11:48.809
a solar power plant
generates electricity

11:48.909 --> 11:50.310
for about eight hours.

11:50.443 --> 11:52.345
All our
electric vehicles are doing

11:52.479 --> 11:54.848
is exporting their emissions
to the power plant.

11:54.982 --> 11:57.417
Our greatest
potential for growth

11:57.550 --> 11:59.352
is in exports.

11:59.486 --> 12:00.988
China only consumes

12:01.088 --> 12:03.857
14% of the world's
petroleum reserves.

12:03.991 --> 12:05.859
India is at 4.9%.

12:05.993 --> 12:07.660
Russia, a little over 3%.

12:07.761 --> 12:11.331
We feel that our
lobbyists' focus

12:11.464 --> 12:14.734
should be on easing
the regulations on exports.

12:14.902 --> 12:17.838
Our LNG exports
to Europe last year

12:17.938 --> 12:19.940
climbed to 64%

12:20.107 --> 12:20.740
- of total exports--
- [clears throat] Bob.

12:20.908 --> 12:22.009
Excuse me, if I may.

12:22.142 --> 12:23.844
What you're not seeing
in the States

12:23.944 --> 12:26.914
is this rabid opposition
to fossil fuels of any kind.

12:27.080 --> 12:28.816
To their use,
to their extraction--

12:28.916 --> 12:31.351
38% of the UK's electricity
came from

12:31.484 --> 12:32.419
natural gas piped in

12:32.585 --> 12:33.453
- from Norway, Steve.
- Gentlemen...

12:33.586 --> 12:35.255
But-but one quarter's from wind,

12:35.422 --> 12:37.457
which I agree is
unreliable and expensive, but--

12:37.590 --> 12:39.192
and this is an important "but"--

12:39.292 --> 12:40.794
- Steve...
- [Bob] Energy consumption

12:40.928 --> 12:42.462
is not a social issue, Steve.

12:42.595 --> 12:44.164
The hell it's not.
It's deeply social.

12:46.066 --> 12:48.435
And we must endeavor ourselves
to educate the world

12:48.568 --> 12:50.570
about our commitment
to cleaner ener--

12:50.703 --> 12:52.639
Steve, will you
shut the fuck up? My God.

12:52.806 --> 12:54.474
This is why
I don't come to these things.

12:55.943 --> 12:58.879
Y'all have been in so many
shareholder meetings, you forgot

12:58.979 --> 13:00.580
what it is
we actually do for a living.

13:00.713 --> 13:02.415
We are well diggers.

13:02.549 --> 13:04.484
We don't, nor can we ever,

13:04.617 --> 13:08.221
control how our product is used
or what it is used for.

13:08.321 --> 13:09.923
There's nothing I can do
to make an engine run cleaner

13:10.057 --> 13:12.159
'cause I don't build
fucking engines.

13:12.292 --> 13:14.561
I don't care what
the governor of California says

13:14.694 --> 13:16.029
about electric vehicles.

13:16.129 --> 13:17.965
I don't care how many
career college students

13:18.131 --> 13:20.700
block London traffic or
spray-paint a fucking sculpture.

13:20.800 --> 13:22.435
I care that the price of oil

13:22.569 --> 13:25.638
stays between
$76 and $88 a barrel.

13:25.805 --> 13:27.975
That is what
we should be discussing.

13:28.108 --> 13:29.676
The world has
already convinced itself

13:29.843 --> 13:31.744
that you are evil and I am evil

13:31.845 --> 13:33.680
for providing them
the one fucking thing

13:33.813 --> 13:35.748
they interact with every day,

13:35.849 --> 13:37.484
and they will not
be convinced otherwise.

13:37.617 --> 13:40.854
Stop wasting your time,
and stop fucking wasting mine.

13:46.994 --> 13:49.396
Gee, Monty,
tell us how you really feel.

13:49.496 --> 13:50.998
[laughter]

13:55.035 --> 13:56.836
You better start caring, Monty.

13:56.970 --> 13:58.838
I mean, your children are
going to inherit an oil fortune,

13:59.006 --> 14:01.008
but your grandchildren won't.

14:01.141 --> 14:02.442
What they inherit,

14:02.575 --> 14:04.177
you're gonna
have to start building now.

14:04.344 --> 14:08.048
I know the party's
not ending tomorrow, but...

14:08.215 --> 14:09.416
it is ending.

14:09.516 --> 14:11.384
<i>♪ quiet, dramatic music ♪</i>

14:11.718 --> 14:13.586
<i>***</i>

14:15.355 --> 14:17.757
[whirring]

14:32.139 --> 14:33.373
[growls softly]

14:33.706 --> 14:35.575
<i>***</i>

14:51.591 --> 14:53.426
[barks softly]

14:54.928 --> 14:57.064
<i>***</i>

15:17.584 --> 15:19.552
<i>***</i>

15:25.758 --> 15:27.494
[squeaks]

15:30.930 --> 15:32.165
[sighs]

15:38.105 --> 15:40.107
<i>***</i>

15:47.714 --> 15:50.250
Are you smiling,
or are you fixin' to bite me?

15:52.419 --> 15:55.088
[barking]

16:00.660 --> 16:02.562
<i>***</i>

16:08.768 --> 16:10.803
We really need
to work this out, you and me.

16:10.970 --> 16:13.040
[panting]

16:22.482 --> 16:24.484
[barks]

16:24.617 --> 16:27.187
Baby steps. Fair enough.

16:30.923 --> 16:32.525
Jefe.

16:32.859 --> 16:34.994
<i>***</i>

16:38.298 --> 16:40.133
Thank you.

16:42.035 --> 16:43.536
I didn't know you could...

16:43.670 --> 16:44.504
Never mind.

16:44.671 --> 16:46.206
What?

16:47.440 --> 16:49.176
Nothing.
It's-it's not my business.

16:50.177 --> 16:51.778
Well, it's my business now.

16:51.911 --> 16:53.413
What'd you want to say?

16:54.714 --> 16:55.748
I-I just, I didn't know

16:55.848 --> 16:58.551
you could drink alcohol
and, uh...

16:58.685 --> 17:01.454
[chuckles] Oh.
More than one is no good,

17:01.588 --> 17:04.191
but one helps my body
produce more milk.

17:08.695 --> 17:11.398
<i>***</i>

17:11.531 --> 17:13.366
It makes you so nervous
to talk about the body

17:13.500 --> 17:16.469
and watch the body do the things
the body's supposed to do.

17:16.569 --> 17:17.704
Why?

17:20.707 --> 17:23.210
I don't know, I think
I'm just younger than you.

17:24.244 --> 17:25.645
You don't look younger.

17:25.778 --> 17:29.048
[chuckles] In life. I...

17:29.216 --> 17:31.884
I mean, this is my first job.

17:33.620 --> 17:35.488
None of my friends are married.

17:35.588 --> 17:38.391
Your baby's the first baby
I've ever been around.

17:38.525 --> 17:40.493
You're the first person
I've ever seen feed one.

17:40.627 --> 17:42.629
[chuckles]

17:42.895 --> 17:45.132
<i>***</i>

17:46.399 --> 17:49.236
Your husband's the first person
I knew who died.

17:49.369 --> 17:51.904
And here I am,
thinking I'm a man.

18:03.916 --> 18:06.085
I asked my grandmother once

18:06.253 --> 18:08.087
how old she felt in her soul.

18:08.255 --> 18:09.689
She was 80,
but I always wondered

18:09.822 --> 18:11.658
if she actually felt 80.

18:11.758 --> 18:15.128
She said, in her heart,
she'll always be 17.

18:17.430 --> 18:18.965
She told me the trick to life

18:19.098 --> 18:21.601
is enduring all the loss
and pain of this place,

18:21.768 --> 18:25.305
but stay 17 in your heart.

18:26.939 --> 18:28.808
<i>***</i>

18:32.245 --> 18:34.214
I wonder if I can do it.

18:39.051 --> 18:41.120
The yard looks nice.

18:41.254 --> 18:42.622
Thank you.

18:45.392 --> 18:47.126
I'll, uh, I'll get started
on the front yard.

18:48.127 --> 18:50.197
I don't care about
the front yard.

18:51.331 --> 18:52.632
Front yard's for
the neighbors to look at.

18:52.765 --> 18:54.167
Backyard's for me.

18:55.268 --> 18:57.237
I'm gonna mow it anyway.

18:57.370 --> 19:00.173
Why mow it when I tell you
I don't want it?

19:03.075 --> 19:04.143
'Cause I...

19:04.311 --> 19:06.446
I don't know how else to help.

19:08.681 --> 19:10.617
<i>***</i>

19:15.655 --> 19:17.190
[whirring]

19:35.608 --> 19:37.244
This motherfucker.

19:38.177 --> 19:40.046
[tires screech]

19:43.650 --> 19:46.386
What the fuck
did I tell you? Huh?

19:47.354 --> 19:48.555
I told you to stay
the fuck away.

19:48.688 --> 19:50.990
Now you're playing husband?
Huh, motherfucker?

19:53.025 --> 19:54.461
Stop it, Manuel! Stop it!

19:54.561 --> 19:56.763
<i>Tengo a mi niño
en la casa, pendejo.</i>

19:56.863 --> 19:58.030
What the fuck is this, huh?

19:58.164 --> 19:59.532
